- You're late.

138
00:11:15,030 --> 00:11:19,639
A wizard is never late, Frodo Baggins.

139
00:11:19,640 --> 00:11:25,640
Nor is he early.
He arrives precisely when he means to.

140
00:11:35,640 --> 00:11:40,040
It's wonderful to see you, Gandalf!

141
00:11:42,540 --> 00:11:47,640
You didn't think I'd miss
your Uncle Bilbo's birthday?

142
00:11:47,940 --> 00:11:50,739
How is the old rascal?

143
00:11:50,740 --> 00:11:54,439
I hear it's going to be a party
of special magnificence.

144
00:11:54,440 --> 00:11:57,039
You know Bilbo.
He's got the whole piece in an uproar.

145
00:11:57,040 --> 00:11:59,139
Well, that should please him.

146
00:11:59,140 --> 00:12:01,339
Half the Shire's been invited.

147
00:12:01,340 --> 00:12:05,340
And the rest of them are turning up anyway.

148
00:12:07,040 --> 00:12:10,639
And so life in the Shire goes on...

149
00:12:10,640 --> 00:12:13,839
... very much as it has this past age.

150
00:12:13,840 --> 00:12:19,439
Full of its own comings and goings,
with change coming slowly.

151
00:12:19,440 --> 00:12:22,739
If it comes at all.

152
00:12:22,740 --> 00:12:26,339
For things are made to endure in the Shire...

153
00:12:26,340 --> 00:12:30,239
...passing from one generation to the next.

154
00:12:30,240 --> 00:12:35,439
There's always been a Baggins
living here under the Hill...

155
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:38,240
...in Bag End.

156
00:12:39,550 --> 00:12:43,049
And there always will be.

157
00:12:43,050 --> 00:12:47,649
To tell you the truth,
Bilbo's been a bit odd lateIy.

158
00:12:47,650 --> 00:12:50,949
I mean, more than usual.

159
00:12:50,950 --> 00:12:54,250
He's taken to locking himself in his study.

160
00:12:54,450 --> 00:12:59,950
He spends hours and hours poring over
old maps when he thinks I'm not looking.

161
00:13:11,350 --> 00:13:14,450
Where's it gone?

162
00:13:39,550 --> 00:13:43,250
He's up to something.

163
00:13:49,950 --> 00:13:52,659
- All right, then. Keep your secrets.
- What?

164
00:13:52,660 --> 00:13:54,649
But I know you have something to do with it.

165
00:13:54,650 --> 00:13:56,159
Good gracious me.

166
00:13:56,160 --> 00:13:59,159
Before you came along, we Bagginses
were very well thought of.

167
00:13:59,160 --> 00:14:00,359
Indeed.

168
00:14:00,360 --> 00:14:03,159
Never had any adventures
or did anything unexpected.

169
00:14:03,160 --> 00:14:09,159
If you're referring to the incident with the dragon.
I was barely involved.

170
00:14:09,160 --> 00:14:12,959
All I did was give your uncle
a little nudge out of the door.

171
00:14:12,960 --> 00:14:17,559
Whatever you did, you've been officially
labeled a disturber of the peace.

172
00:14:17,560 --> 00:14:20,860
Oh, really?

173
00:14:25,060 --> 00:14:28,460
Gandalf! Gandalf!

174
00:14:33,160 --> 00:14:35,860
Fireworks, Gandalf!

175
00:14:37,460 --> 00:14:41,460
- Gandalf!
- Fireworks, Gandalf!

176
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:00,559
Gandalf?

177
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:05,960
- I'm glad you're back.
- So am I, dear boy.

178
00:15:09,060 --> 00:15:12,360
So am I.

179
00:15:42,770 --> 00:15:44,369
No, thank you!

180
00:15:44,370 --> 00:15:48,569
We don't want any more visitors,
well-wishers or distant relations!

181
00:15:48,570 --> 00:15:53,370
And what about very old friends?

182
00:15:55,270 --> 00:15:57,569
Gandalf?

183
00:15:57,570 --> 00:16:01,269
- Bilbo Baggins.
- My dear Gandalf!

184
00:16:01,270 --> 00:16:07,670
Good to see you. 111 years old!
Who would believe it?

185
00:16:08,170 --> 00:16:11,570
You haven't aged a day.

186
00:16:16,770 --> 00:16:18,969
Come on, come in!

187
00:16:18,970 --> 00:16:22,579
Welcome, welcome.

188
00:16:22,580 --> 00:16:26,480
Oh, here we are.

189
00:16:26,780 --> 00:16:29,379
Tea...or maybe something a littIe stronger?

190
00:16:29,380 --> 00:16:33,379
I've got a few bottles of the old winyard left - 1296.

191
00:16:33,380 --> 00:16:38,579
Very good year. Almost as old as I am.

192
00:16:38,580 --> 00:16:43,279
It was laid down by my father.
What say we open one, eh?

193
00:16:43,280 --> 00:16:47,280
Just tea, thank you.

194
00:16:52,380 --> 00:16:54,179
I was expecting you sometime last week.

195
00:16:54,180 --> 00:16:57,679
Not that it matters. You come and go as
you please. Always have and always will.

196
00:16:57,680 --> 00:17:03,079
You caught me a bit unprepared I'm afraid.
We've only got cold chicken and a bit of pickle....

197
00:17:03,080 --> 00:17:06,679
There's some cheese here.
No, that won't do.

198
00:17:06,680 --> 00:17:11,279
We've got raspberry jam, an apple tart....

199
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:15,479
But not much for afters.
Oh, no, we're all right.

200
00:17:15,480 --> 00:17:19,680
I've just found some sponge cake.

201
00:17:21,280 --> 00:17:23,980
I could make you some eggs if you'd li...

202
00:17:26,390 --> 00:17:30,089
- Just tea, thank you.
- Oh, right.

203
00:17:30,090 --> 00:17:33,579
- You don't mind if I eat, do you?
- No, not at all.

204
00:17:33,580 --> 00:17:35,679
Bilbo! Bilbo Baggins!

205
00:17:35,680 --> 00:17:38,680
I'm not at home!

206
00:17:43,290 --> 00:17:46,089
It's the Sackville-Bagginses.

207
00:17:46,090 --> 00:17:48,789
- I know you're in there!
- They're after the house.

208
00:17:48,790 --> 00:17:51,489
They've never forgiven me for living this long.

209
00:17:51,490 --> 00:17:54,389
I've got to get away from these confounded
relatives, hanging on the bell all day...

210
00:17:54,390 --> 00:17:57,189
...never giving me a moment's peace.

211
00:17:57,190 --> 00:18:00,889
I want to see mountains again.
Mountains, Gandalf!

212
00:18:00,890 --> 00:18:05,589
And then find somewhere quiet
where I can finish my book. Oh, tea.

213
00:18:05,590 --> 00:18:09,789
- So you mean to go through with your plan?
- Yes, yes. It's all in hand.

214
00:18:09,790 --> 00:18:13,390
All the arrangements are made.

215
00:18:14,090 --> 00:18:16,289
Oh, thank you.

216
00:18:16,290 --> 00:18:18,589
Frodo suspects something.

217
00:18:18,590 --> 00:18:21,289
Of course he does. He's a Baggins...

218
00:18:21,290 --> 00:18:24,489
...not some blockheaded Bracegirdle
from Hardbottle.

219
00:18:24,490 --> 00:18:28,089
You will tell him, won't you?

220
00:18:28,090 --> 00:18:31,590
- Yes, yes.
- He's very fond of you.

221
00:18:32,390 --> 00:18:35,390
I know.

222
00:18:36,290 --> 00:18:40,299
He'd probably come with me if I asked him.

223
00:18:40,300 --> 00:18:45,000
I think in his heart, Frodo's
still in love with the Shire.

224
00:18:45,200 --> 00:18:47,799
The woods, the fields.

225
00:18:47,800 --> 00:18:51,500
Little rivers.

226
00:18:54,600 --> 00:18:58,700
I am old, Gandalf.

227
00:18:58,700 --> 00:19:05,200
I know I don't look it, but I'm
beginning to feel it in my heart.

228
00:19:06,100 --> 00:19:08,799
I feel thin.

229
00:19:08,800 --> 00:19:11,799
Sort of stretched...

230
00:19:11,800 --> 00:19:15,399
...like butter scraped over too much bread.

231
00:19:15,400 --> 00:19:19,999
I need a holiday. A very Long holiday.

232
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:24,600
And I don't expect I shall return.

233
00:19:25,500 --> 00:19:30,100
In fact, I mean not to.

234
00:19:31,300 --> 00:19:36,700
Old Toby.
The finest weed in the Southfarthing.

235
00:19:52,800 --> 00:19:55,499
Gandalf, my old friend...

236
00:19:55,500 --> 00:19:59,700
...this will be a night to remember.

237
00:20:21,110 --> 00:20:22,509
Hello, hello.

238
00:20:22,510 --> 00:20:27,609
Fatty Bolger. Lovely to see you.
Welcome, welcome.

239
00:20:27,610 --> 00:20:31,510
Go on, Sam. Ask Rosie for a dance.

240
00:20:32,710 --> 00:20:37,309
- I think I'll just have another ale.
- Oh, no, you don't.

241
00:20:37,310 --> 00:20:40,610
Go on!

242
00:20:49,310 --> 00:20:51,309
So there I was...

243
00:20:51,310 --> 00:20:55,609
...at the mercy of three monstrous trolls.

244
00:20:55,610 --> 00:20:57,709
And they were all arguing amongst themselves...

245
00:20:57,710 --> 00:21:00,309
...about how they were going to cook us.

246
00:21:00,310 --> 00:21:06,409
Whether it be turned on a spit, or to sit
on us one by one, squash us into jelly.

247
00:21:06,410 --> 00:21:10,109
They spent so much time arguing
the whithertos and the whyfors...

248
00:21:10,110 --> 00:21:14,719
...that the sun's first light
crept over the top of the trees...

249
00:21:14,720 --> 00:21:18,620
...and turned them all to stone!

250
00:21:22,620 --> 00:21:25,420
Quickly.

251
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:31,620
Up they go!

252
00:21:33,020 --> 00:21:35,820
No no, the big one - big one

253
00:21:43,420 --> 00:21:46,419
Mrs. Bracegirdle, how nice to see you.
Welcome, welcome.

254
00:21:46,420 --> 00:21:48,519
Are all these children yours?

255
00:21:48,520 --> 00:21:52,920
Good gracious, you have been productive.

256
00:21:53,520 --> 00:21:56,320
Bilbo?

257
00:21:56,520 --> 00:21:58,519
Sackville-Bagginses!

258
00:21:58,520 --> 00:22:01,020
Quickly, hide!

259
00:22:09,520 --> 00:22:13,120
Thank you, my boy.

260
00:22:13,220 --> 00:22:16,819
You're a good lad, Frodo.

261
00:22:16,820 --> 00:22:20,019
I'm very selfish, you know.

262
00:22:20,020 --> 00:22:23,929
Yes, I am. Very selfish.

263
00:22:23,930 --> 00:22:26,329
I don't know why I took you in after
your mother and father died...

264
00:22:26,330 --> 00:22:28,419
...but it wasn't out of charity.

265
00:22:28,420 --> 00:22:29,919
I think it was because...

266
00:22:29,920 --> 00:22:32,519
...of all my numerous relations...

267
00:22:32,520 --> 00:22:36,429
...you were the one Baggins that showed real spirit.

268
00:22:36,430 --> 00:22:38,429
Bilbo, have you been at the Gaffer's home brew?

269
00:22:38,430 --> 00:22:40,329
No.

270
00:22:40,330 --> 00:22:43,229
Well, yes, but that's not the point.

271
00:22:43,230 --> 00:22:47,830
The point is, Frodo...

272
00:22:49,530 --> 00:22:52,930
...you'll be all right.

273
00:22:54,930 --> 00:22:57,129
- Done!
- You're supposed to stick it in the ground.

274
00:22:57,130 --> 00:22:58,829
- It is in the ground.
- Outside!

275
00:22:58,830 --> 00:23:01,830
This was your idea.

276
00:23:16,230 --> 00:23:18,929
Bilbo.

277
00:23:18,930 --> 00:23:21,829
Bilbo, watch out for the dragon!

278
00:23:21,830 --> 00:23:26,630
Nonsense. There hasn't been a dragon
in these parts for thousands of years.

279
00:23:38,740 --> 00:23:43,640
- That was good.
- Let's get another one.

280
00:23:43,640 --> 00:23:48,339
Meriadoc Brandybuck and Peregrin Took.

281
00:23:48,340 --> 00:23:51,640
I might've known.

282
00:23:56,140 --> 00:23:59,139
Speech, Bilbo!

283
00:23:59,140 --> 00:24:00,639
Speech!

284
00:24:00,640 --> 00:24:03,140
Speech!

285
00:24:06,940 --> 00:24:09,939
My dear Bagginses and Boffins...

286
00:24:09,940 --> 00:24:12,339
...Tooks and Brandybucks...

287
00:24:12,340 --> 00:24:15,039
...Grubbs, Chubbs...

288
00:24:15,040 --> 00:24:17,239
...Hornblowers...

289
00:24:17,240 --> 00:24:19,339
...Bolgers...

290
00:24:19,340 --> 00:24:21,139
...Bracegirdles...

291
00:24:21,140 --> 00:24:25,140
...and Proudfoots.
- Proudfeet!

292
00:24:25,940 --> 00:24:28,440
Today is my 111th birthday!

293
00:24:28,840 --> 00:24:31,539
Happy birthday!

294
00:24:32,540 --> 00:24:37,039
But alas, eleventh-one years is
far too short a time to live among...

295
00:24:37,040 --> 00:24:40,939
...such excellent and admirable Hobbits.

296
00:24:40,940 --> 00:24:43,849
I don't know half of you
half as well as I should like...

297
00:24:43,850 --> 00:24:49,750
...and I like less than half of you
half as well as you deserve.

298
00:24:58,450 --> 00:25:02,150
I have things to do.

299
00:25:07,150 --> 00:25:10,650
I've put this off for far too long.

300
00:25:13,150 --> 00:25:18,249
I regret to announce this is the end!

301
00:25:18,250 --> 00:25:20,549
I'm going now.

302
00:25:20,550 --> 00:25:24,850
I bid you all a very fond farewell.

303
00:25:25,750 --> 00:25:28,450
Goodbye.

304
00:26:00,250 --> 00:26:03,659
I suppose you think that was terribly clever.

305
00:26:03,660 --> 00:26:07,159
Come on, Gandalf.
Did you see their faces?

306
00:26:07,160 --> 00:26:10,059
There are many magic rings in
this world, Bilbo Baggins...

307
00:26:10,060 --> 00:26:12,449
...and none of them should be used lightly.

308
00:26:12,450 --> 00:26:14,759
It was just a bit of fun.

309
00:26:14,760 --> 00:26:19,860
Oh, you're probably right, as usual.

310
00:26:19,860 --> 00:26:23,659
- You will keep an eye on Frodo, won't you?
- Two eyes.

311
00:26:23,660 --> 00:26:26,459
As often as I can spare them.

312
00:26:26,460 --> 00:26:29,859
- I'm leaving everything to him.
- What about this ring of yours?

313
00:26:29,860 --> 00:26:33,859
- Is that staying too?
- Yes, yes.

314
00:26:33,860 --> 00:26:38,759
It's in an envelope over there on the mantelpiece.

315
00:26:38,760 --> 00:26:43,160
No. Wait, it is...

316
00:26:44,260 --> 00:26:48,360
...here in my pocket.

317
00:26:51,460 --> 00:26:56,160
Isn't that--? Isn't that odd, now?

318
00:26:56,460 --> 00:27:01,360
Yet, after all, why not?

319
00:27:01,460 --> 00:27:06,759
- Why shouldn't I keep it?
- I think you should leave the ring behind.

320
00:27:06,760 --> 00:27:09,159
Is that so hard?

321
00:27:09,160 --> 00:27:11,960
Well, no.

322
00:27:12,960 --> 00:27:15,860
And yes.

323
00:27:16,370 --> 00:27:19,769
Now it comes to it,
I don't feel l ike parting with it.

324
00:27:19,770 --> 00:27:21,769
It's mine. I found it! It came to me!

325
00:27:21,770 --> 00:27:26,269
- There's no need to get angry.
- Well, if I'm angry, it's your fault!

326
00:27:26,270 --> 00:27:29,470
It's mine.

327
00:27:29,470 --> 00:27:32,269
My own.

328
00:27:32,270 --> 00:27:36,469
- My precious.
- Precious?

329
00:27:36,470 --> 00:27:39,569
It's been called that before, but not by you.

330
00:27:39,570 --> 00:27:42,269
What business is it of yours
what I do with my own things?

331
00:27:42,270 --> 00:27:45,269
I think you've had that ring quite long enough.

332
00:27:45,270 --> 00:27:48,269
- You want it for yourself!
- Bilbo Baggins!

333
00:27:48,270 --> 00:27:52,769
Do not take me for some conjurer of cheap tricks.

334
00:27:52,770 --> 00:27:57,770
I am not trying to rob you.

335
00:28:01,470 --> 00:28:04,570
I'm trying to help you.

336
00:28:11,570 --> 00:28:15,269
All your long years, we've been friends.

337
00:28:15,270 --> 00:28:18,870
Trust me as you once did.

338
00:28:19,370 --> 00:28:22,279
Let it go.

339
00:28:22,280 --> 00:28:26,080
You're right, Gandalf.

340
00:28:26,780 --> 00:28:30,869
The ring must go to Frodo.

341
00:28:30,870 --> 00:28:34,079
It's late. The road is long.

342
00:28:34,080 --> 00:28:37,980
Yes, it is time.

343
00:28:39,280 --> 00:28:45,580
Bilbo, the ring is still in your pocket.

344
00:29:19,080 --> 00:29:23,480
I've thought up an ending for my book:

345
00:29:23,680 --> 00:29:28,979
"And he lived happily ever after
to the end of his days."

346
00:29:28,980 --> 00:29:33,379
And I'm sure you will, my dear friend.

347
00:29:33,380 --> 00:29:36,280
Goodbye, Gandalf.

348
00:29:37,380 --> 00:29:41,580
Goodbye, dear Bilbo.

349
00:29:47,990 --> 00:29:53,590
<i>The road goes ever on and on...</i>

350
00:29:54,790 --> 00:29:58,690
Until our next meeting.

351
00:30:24,590 --> 00:30:28,389
It's mine. My own.

352
00:30:28,390 --> 00:30:32,089
My precious.

353
00:30:32,090 --> 00:30:35,289
Riddles in the dark.

354
00:30:35,290 --> 00:30:36,889
Bilbo!

355
00:30:36,890 --> 00:30:39,790
Bilbo!

356
00:30:42,090 --> 00:30:46,490
My precious.

357
00:30:46,590 --> 00:30:48,989
Precious.

358
00:30:48,990 --> 00:30:52,890
He's gone, hasn't he?

359
00:30:54,390 --> 00:30:57,589
He talked for so long about leaving...

360
00:30:57,590 --> 00:31:01,690
...I didn't think he'd really do it.

361
00:31:04,800 --> 00:31:08,200
Gandalf?

362
00:31:14,950 --> 00:31:16,949
Bilbo's ring.

363
00:31:16,950 --> 00:31:19,549
He's gone to stay with the elves.

364
00:31:19,550 --> 00:31:23,950
He's left you Bag End.

365
00:31:26,250 --> 00:31:28,949
Along with all his possessions.

366
00:31:28,950 --> 00:31:33,250
The ring is yours now.

367
00:31:34,450 --> 00:31:38,049
- Put it somewhere out of sight.
- Where are you going?

368
00:31:38,050 --> 00:31:40,549
- There are some things that I must see to.
- What things?

369
00:31:40,550 --> 00:31:45,749
- Questions. Questions that need answering.
- You've only just arrived.

370
00:31:45,750 --> 00:31:49,750
I don't understand.

371
00:31:51,650 --> 00:31:54,150
Neither do I.

372
00:31:55,950 --> 00:31:58,449
Keep it secret.

373
00:31:58,450 --> 00:32:01,750
Keep it safe.

374
00:32:35,250 --> 00:32:37,749
Shire!

375
00:32:37,750 --> 00:32:40,550
Baggins!

376
00:32:40,970 --> 00:32:50,459
<i><font color="#778899">♫ Nêbâbîtham Magânanê</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(We renounce our Maker)</font></i>

377
00:33:29,350 --> 00:33:32,449
"The year 3434 of the second age.

378
00:33:32,450 --> 00:33:37,049
Here follows the account of Isildur,
High King of Gondor...

379
00:33:37,050 --> 00:33:42,150
...and the finding of the ring of power."

380
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:53,400
<i><font color="#0080C0">♫ I tuo, i macil</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(The strength, the weapon)</font></i>

381
00:33:44,250 --> 00:33:46,349
"It has come to me.

382
00:33:46,350 --> 00:33:49,949
The one ring.
It shall be an heirloom of my kingdom.

383
00:33:49,950 --> 00:33:53,400
All those who follow in my bloodline
shall be bound to its fate...

384
00:33:53,640 --> 00:34:11,000
<i><font color="#0080C0">♫ Á lelyat túrenna!</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Go to victory!)</font></i>

385
00:33:53,650 --> 00:33:57,649
...for I will risk no hurt to the ring.

386
00:33:57,650 --> 00:34:01,049
It is precious to me...

387
00:34:01,050 --> 00:34:05,000
...though I buy it with great pain.

388
00:34:05,100 --> 00:34:11,000
<i><font color="#FF0000">Zigur...</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Sauron...)</font></i>

389
00:34:06,750 --> 00:34:11,000
The markings upon the band begin to fade.

390
00:34:11,250 --> 00:34:16,249
The writing, which at first was as clear
as red flame, has all but disappeared.

391
00:34:16,250 --> 00:34:21,550
A secret now that only fire can tell."

392
00:34:36,850 --> 00:34:39,949
Shire...

393
00:34:39,950 --> 00:34:42,449
...Baggins.

394
00:34:42,450 --> 00:34:47,850
There's no Bagginses around here.
They're all up in Hobbiton.

395
00:34:48,150 --> 00:34:51,050
That way.

396
00:34:53,350 --> 00:34:55,649
<i>"Hey ho to the dock I go</i>

397
00:34:55,650 --> 00:34:58,049
<i>To heal my heart and drown my woe</i>

398
00:34:58,050 --> 00:35:00,549
<i>Rain may fall and wind may blow</i>

399
00:35:00,550 --> 00:35:02,749
<i>But there still be...</i>

400
00:35:02,750 --> 00:35:04,349
<i>...many miles to go</i>

401
00:35:04,350 --> 00:35:06,549
<i>Sweet is the sound of the pouring rain</i>

402
00:35:06,550 --> 00:35:08,949
<i>And the stream that falls from hill to plain</i>

403
00:35:08,950 --> 00:35:10,949
<i>Better than rain or rippling brook</i>

404
00:35:10,950 --> 00:35:14,750
<i>Is a mug of beer inside this Took!"</i>

405
00:35:16,750 --> 00:35:19,959
There's been some strange folk crossing the Shire.

406
00:35:19,960 --> 00:35:24,349
Dwarves and others of a less than savory nature.

407
00:35:24,350 --> 00:35:26,559
War is brewing.

408
00:35:26,560 --> 00:35:29,459
The mountains are fair teeming with goblins.

409
00:35:29,460 --> 00:35:32,249
Far-off tales and children's stories, that's all that is.

410
00:35:32,250 --> 00:35:36,959
You're beginning to sound like that old
Bilbo Baggins. Cracked, he was.

411
00:35:36,960 --> 00:35:40,159
Young Mr. Frodo here, he's cracking.

412
00:35:40,160 --> 00:35:41,659
And proud of it.

413
00:35:41,660 --> 00:35:44,259
- Cheers, Gaffer.
- Aye. Cheers.

414
00:35:44,260 --> 00:35:48,559
Weel it's none of our concern what
goes on beyond our borders.

415
00:35:48,560 --> 00:35:54,060
Keep your nose out of trouble,
and no trouble'll come to you.

416
00:35:56,160 --> 00:35:58,459
- Good night, lads.
- Good night.

417
00:35:58,460 --> 00:36:03,159
Good night, sweet maiden of the golden ale.

418
00:36:03,160 --> 00:36:05,759
Mind who you're sweet-taking.

419
00:36:05,760 --> 00:36:11,249
Don't worry, Sam.
Rosie knows an idiot when she sees one.

420
00:36:11,250 --> 00:36:13,059
Does she?

421
00:36:13,060 --> 00:36:17,460
- Good night, Sam.
- Good night, Mr. Frodo.

422
00:36:40,860 --> 00:36:44,760
Is it secret? Is it safe?

423
00:36:52,260 --> 00:36:55,760
What are you doing?

424
00:37:06,960 --> 00:37:09,759
Hold out your hand, Frodo.

425
00:37:09,760 --> 00:37:12,360
It's quite cool.

426
00:37:14,360 --> 00:37:17,560
What can you see?

427
00:37:17,960 --> 00:37:21,760
Can you see anything?

428
00:37:23,160 --> 00:37:25,059
Nothing.

429
00:37:25,060 --> 00:37:28,259
There's nothing.

430
00:37:28,260 --> 00:37:31,160
Wait.

431
00:37:33,100 --> 00:37:35,500
<i><font color="#FF0000">Zigur...</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Sauron...)</font></i>

432
00:37:33,760 --> 00:37:37,460
There are markings.

433
00:37:37,560 --> 00:37:41,159
It's some form of Elvish.
I can't read it.

434
00:37:41,160 --> 00:37:44,259
There are few who can.

435
00:37:44,260 --> 00:37:49,759
The language is that of Mordor,
which I will not utter here.

436
00:37:49,760 --> 00:37:51,059
Mordor!

437
00:37:51,060 --> 00:37:53,259
In the common tongue, it says:

438
00:37:53,260 --> 00:37:57,059
"One ring to rule them all...

439
00:37:57,060 --> 00:37:59,559
...One ring to find them...

440
00:37:59,560 --> 00:38:02,059
...One ring to bring them all...

441
00:38:02,060 --> 00:38:06,460
...and in the darkness bind them."

442
00:38:06,760 --> 00:38:08,859
This is the One ring...

443
00:38:08,860 --> 00:38:14,459
...forged by the Dark Lord Sauron
in the fires of Mount Doom.

444
00:38:14,460 --> 00:38:19,259
Taken by IsiIdur from the hand of Sauron himself.

445
00:38:19,260 --> 00:38:22,159
Bilbo found it.

446
00:38:22,160 --> 00:38:24,359
- In Gollum's cave.
- Yes.

447
00:38:24,360 --> 00:38:29,159
For 60 years, the ring lay quiet in Bilbo's keeping...

448
00:38:29,160 --> 00:38:33,159
...prolonging his life, delaying old age.

449
00:38:33,160 --> 00:38:37,759
But no longer, Frodo.
Evil is stirring in Mordor.

450
00:38:37,760 --> 00:38:40,359
The ring has awoken.

451
00:38:40,360 --> 00:38:43,259
It's heard its master's call.

452
00:38:43,260 --> 00:38:48,000
But he was destroyed.
Sauron was destroyed.

453
00:38:48,100 --> 00:38:50,500
<i><font color="#FF0000">Zigur...</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Sauron...)</font></i>

454
00:38:52,860 --> 00:38:55,959
No, Frodo.

455
00:38:55,960 --> 00:38:59,459
The spirit of Sauron endured.

456
00:38:59,460 --> 00:39:05,059
His life force is bound to the ring,
and the ring survived.

457
00:39:05,060 --> 00:39:08,259
Sauron has returned.

458
00:39:08,260 --> 00:39:10,559
His orcs have multiplied.

459
00:39:10,560 --> 00:39:14,659
His fortress at Barad-dûr
is rebuilt in the land of Mordor.

460
00:39:14,660 --> 00:39:19,669
Sauron needs only this ring to cover
all the lands in a second darkness.

461
00:39:19,670 --> 00:39:21,959
He is seeking it.

462
00:39:21,960 --> 00:39:26,059
Seeking it - All his thought is bent on it.

463
00:39:26,060 --> 00:39:28,959
For the ring yearns above all else...

464
00:39:28,960 --> 00:39:32,659
...to return to the hand of its master.

465
00:39:32,660 --> 00:39:34,459
They are one...

466
00:39:34,460 --> 00:39:37,859
...the ring and the Dark Lord.

467
00:39:37,860 --> 00:39:39,359
Frodo...

468
00:39:39,360 --> 00:39:41,459
...he must never find it.

469
00:39:41,460 --> 00:39:42,869
All right.

470
00:39:42,870 --> 00:39:47,469
We put it away. We keep it hidden.
We never speak of it again.

471
00:39:47,470 --> 00:39:51,470
No one knows it's here, do they?

472
00:39:55,770 --> 00:39:57,969
Do they, Gandalf?

473
00:39:57,970 --> 00:40:02,669
There is one other who knew
that Bilbo had the ring.

474
00:40:02,670 --> 00:40:05,869
I looked everywhere for the creature Gollum.

475
00:40:05,870 --> 00:40:09,370
But the enemy found him first.

476
00:40:09,770 --> 00:40:12,469
I don't know how long they tortured him.

477
00:40:12,470 --> 00:40:17,069
But amidst the endless screams and
inane babble, they discerned two words:

478
00:40:17,070 --> 00:40:19,469
Shire!

479
00:40:19,470 --> 00:40:21,269
Baggins!

480
00:40:21,270 --> 00:40:23,269
Shire.

481
00:40:23,270 --> 00:40:27,470
Baggins.
But that would lead them here!

482
00:40:28,970 --> 00:40:31,470
Who goes there?

483
00:40:31,770 --> 00:40:33,469
Take it, Gandalf!

484
00:40:33,470 --> 00:40:34,569
- Take it!
- No, Frodo.

485
00:40:34,570 --> 00:40:37,169
- You must take it!
- You cannot offer me this ring!

486
00:40:37,170 --> 00:40:41,870
- I'm giving it to you!
- Don't tempt me, Frodo!

487
00:40:42,070 --> 00:40:44,569
I dare not take it.

488
00:40:44,570 --> 00:40:48,169
Not even to keep it safe.

489
00:40:48,170 --> 00:40:50,869
Understand, Frodo...

490
00:40:50,870 --> 00:40:55,870
...I would use this ring from a desire to do good.

491
00:40:59,870 --> 00:41:06,269
But through me, it would wield a power
too great and terrible to imagine.

492
00:41:06,270 --> 00:41:10,570
- But it cannot stay in the Shire!
- No.

493
00:41:11,070 --> 00:41:14,070
No, it can't.

494
00:41:17,970 --> 00:41:20,870
What must I do?

495
00:41:21,070 --> 00:41:24,869
- You must leave. And leave quickly.
- Where? Where do I go?

496
00:41:24,870 --> 00:41:28,369
Get out of the Shire.
Make for the village of Bree.

497
00:41:28,370 --> 00:41:29,669
Bree.

498
00:41:29,670 --> 00:41:32,569
- What about you?
- I'll be waiting for you...

499
00:41:32,570 --> 00:41:35,269
...at the inn of the Prancing Pony.

500
00:41:35,270 --> 00:41:39,169
- And the ring will be safe there?
- I don't know, Frodo.

501
00:41:39,170 --> 00:41:42,570
I don't have any answers.

502
00:41:42,670 --> 00:41:48,369
I must see the head of my order.
He is both wise and powerful. Trust me, Frodo.

503
00:41:48,370 --> 00:41:51,169
He'll know what to do.

504
00:41:51,170 --> 00:41:54,269
You'll have to leave the name
of Baggins behind you.

505
00:41:54,270 --> 00:41:57,369
That name is not safe outside the Shire.

506
00:41:57,370 --> 00:42:01,369
Travel only by day.
And stay off the road.

507
00:42:01,370 --> 00:42:05,970
I can cut across country easily enough.

508
00:42:07,070 --> 00:42:08,669
My dear Frodo.

509
00:42:08,670 --> 00:42:11,869
Hobbits really are amazing creatures.

510
00:42:11,870 --> 00:42:14,969
You can learn all that there is to
know about their ways in a month.

511
00:42:14,970 --> 00:42:17,569
And yet, after a hundred years...

512
00:42:17,570 --> 00:42:20,970
...they can still surprise you.

513
00:42:21,270 --> 00:42:24,070
Get down.

514
00:42:34,770 --> 00:42:38,469
Confound it all, Samwise Gamgee!
Have you been eavesdropping?

515
00:42:38,470 --> 00:42:40,169
I haven't been dropping no eaves. Honest.

516
00:42:40,170 --> 00:42:43,169
I was just cutting the grass under
the window there...If you follow me.

517
00:42:43,170 --> 00:42:45,769
A little late for trimming the verge, don't you think?

518
00:42:45,770 --> 00:42:48,769
- I heard raised voices.
- What did you hear? Speak!

519
00:42:48,770 --> 00:42:50,469
Nothing important.

520
00:42:50,470 --> 00:42:52,969
That is, I heard a good deal
about a ring, and a Dark Lord...

521
00:42:52,970 --> 00:42:54,669
...and something about the end of the world but...

522
00:42:54,670 --> 00:43:00,269
Please, Mr. Gandalf, sir, don't hurt me.
Don't turn me into anything unnatural.

523
00:43:00,270 --> 00:43:03,069
No?

524
00:43:03,070 --> 00:43:05,469
Perhaps not.

525
00:43:05,470 --> 00:43:10,270
I've thought of a better use for you.

526
00:43:10,570 --> 00:43:14,970
Come along, Samwise. Keep up.

527
00:43:15,170 --> 00:43:17,679
Be careful, both of you.

528
00:43:17,680 --> 00:43:20,569
The enemy has many spies in his service:

529
00:43:20,570 --> 00:43:24,870
Birds, beasts.

530
00:43:25,270 --> 00:43:28,570
Is it safe?

531
00:43:28,780 --> 00:43:30,369
Never put it on...

532
00:43:30,370 --> 00:43:33,869
...for the agents of the Dark Lord
will be drawn to its power.

533
00:43:33,870 --> 00:43:35,969
Always remember, Frodo...

534
00:43:35,970 --> 00:43:39,579
...the ring is trying to get back to its master.

535
00:43:39,580 --> 00:43:43,080
It wants to be found.

536
00:44:22,180 --> 00:44:24,779
This is it.

537
00:44:24,780 --> 00:44:27,179
This is what?

538
00:44:27,180 --> 00:44:29,779
If I take one more step...

539
00:44:29,780 --> 00:44:34,980
...it'll be the farthest away
from home I've ever been.

540
00:44:37,980 --> 00:44:40,880
Come on, Sam.

541
00:44:47,880 --> 00:44:50,279
Remember what Bilbo used to say:

542
00:44:50,280 --> 00:44:54,179
- "It's a dangerous business, Frodo."
- "Going out your door.

543
00:44:54,180 --> 00:44:58,779
You step onto the road,
and if you don't keep your feet...

544
00:44:58,780 --> 00:45:04,280
... there's no knowing where
you might be swept off to."

545
00:45:09,500 --> 00:45:15,500
<i><font color="#008000">♫ Rîn athar annún-aearath</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(O Queen beyond the Western Seas)</font></i>

546
00:45:16,880 --> 00:45:18,080
Sam.

547
00:45:18,500 --> 00:45:25,500
<i><font color="#008000">♫ Calad ammen i reniar</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(O light to us that wander)</font></i>

548
00:45:22,180 --> 00:45:24,780
Wood-elves.

549
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:36,000
<i><font color="#008000">♫ Mi 'aladhremmin ennorath</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Amid the tree-woven lands of Middle-earth.)</font></i>

550
00:45:37,300 --> 00:45:46,000
<i><font color="#008000">♫ A Elbereth Gilthoniel</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Elbereth Star-kindler)</font></i>

551
00:45:37,500 --> 00:45:41,079
They're going to the harbor
beyond the White Towers.

552
00:45:41,080 --> 00:45:43,379
To the Grey Havens.

553
00:45:43,380 --> 00:45:45,579
They're leaving Middle-earth.

554
00:45:45,580 --> 00:45:47,800
Never to return.

555
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:56,000
<i><font color="#008000">♫ I chin a thûl lín míriel...</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Your eyes and breath, like shining jewels...)</font></i>

556
00:45:50,680 --> 00:45:53,579
I don't know why...

557
00:45:53,580 --> 00:45:57,380
...it makes me sad.

558
00:45:57,980 --> 00:46:03,379
Everywhere I lie there's a dirty
great root sticking into my back.

559
00:46:03,380 --> 00:46:05,279
Just shut your eyes...

560
00:46:05,280 --> 00:46:08,279
...and imagine you're back in your own bed...

561
00:46:08,280 --> 00:46:13,580
...with a soft mattress and a lovely feather pillow.

562
00:46:21,480 --> 00:46:24,279
It's not working, Mr. Frodo.

563
00:46:24,280 --> 00:46:28,580
I'm never going to be able to sleep out here.

564
00:46:29,480 --> 00:46:33,280
Me neither, Sam.

565
00:47:00,380 --> 00:47:03,679
Smoke rises from the Mountain of Doom.

566
00:47:03,680 --> 00:47:05,479
The hour grows late.

567
00:47:05,480 --> 00:47:09,379
And Gandalf the Grey rides to Isengard...

568
00:47:09,380 --> 00:47:11,979
...seeking my counsel.

569
00:47:11,980 --> 00:47:16,079
For that is why you have come, is it not?

570
00:47:16,080 --> 00:47:17,679
My old friend.

571
00:47:17,680 --> 00:47:20,680
Saruman.

572
00:47:24,080 --> 00:47:27,879
- You are sure of this?
- Beyond any doubt.

573
00:47:27,880 --> 00:47:30,389
So the ring of power has been found.

574
00:47:30,390 --> 00:47:33,779
All these long years, it was in the Shire.

575
00:47:33,780 --> 00:47:37,589
- Under my very nose.
- Yet you did not have the wit to see it.

576
00:47:37,590 --> 00:47:42,689
Your love of the halfling's leaf
has clearly slowed your mind.

577
00:47:42,690 --> 00:47:47,089
But we still have time.
Time enough to counter Sauron if we act quickly.

578
00:47:47,090 --> 00:47:49,589
Time?

579
00:47:49,590 --> 00:47:52,589
What time do you think we have?

580
00:47:52,590 --> 00:47:56,689
Sauron has regained much of his former strength.

581
00:47:56,690 --> 00:47:59,079
He cannot yet take physical form...

582
00:47:59,080 --> 00:48:02,389
...but his spirit has lost none of its potency.

583
00:48:02,390 --> 00:48:08,089
Concealed within his fortress,
the Lord of Mordor sees all.

584
00:48:08,090 --> 00:48:15,290
His gaze pierces cloud, shadow, earth and flesh.

585
00:48:15,590 --> 00:48:19,589
You know of what I speak, Gandalf.

586
00:48:19,590 --> 00:48:25,789
A great eye, lidless, wreathed in flame.

587
00:48:25,790 --> 00:48:27,789
The eye of Sauron.

588
00:48:27,790 --> 00:48:30,789
He is gathering all evil to him.

589
00:48:30,790 --> 00:48:32,789
Very soon, he'll have summoned an army...

590
00:48:32,790 --> 00:48:35,989
...great enough for an assault upon Middle-earth.

591
00:48:35,990 --> 00:48:38,889
You know this?

592
00:48:38,890 --> 00:48:40,989
How?

593
00:48:40,990 --> 00:48:43,089
I have seen it.

594
00:48:43,090 --> 00:48:47,089
A palantir is a dangerous tool, Saruman.

595
00:48:47,090 --> 00:48:48,989
Why?

596
00:48:48,990 --> 00:48:53,090
Why should we fear to use it?

597
00:48:54,390 --> 00:48:58,489
They are not all accounted for,
the lost seeing-stones.

598
00:48:58,490 --> 00:49:03,090
We do not know who else may be watching.

599
00:49:04,290 --> 00:49:07,189
The hour is later than you think.

600
00:49:07,190 --> 00:49:10,990
Sauron's forces are already moving.

601
00:49:11,790 --> 00:49:14,889
The Nine have left Minas Morgul.

602
00:49:14,890 --> 00:49:16,089
The Nine?

603
00:49:16,090 --> 00:49:19,389
They crossed the river Isen on Midsummer's Eve...

604
00:49:19,390 --> 00:49:22,289
...disguised as riders in black.

605
00:49:22,290 --> 00:49:27,590
- They've reached the Shire?
- They will find the ring.

606
00:49:27,790 --> 00:49:30,489
And kill the one who carries it.

607
00:49:30,490 --> 00:49:33,390
Frodo!

608
00:49:44,690 --> 00:49:49,789
You did not seriously think that a hobbit
could contend with the will of Sauron?

609
00:49:49,790 --> 00:49:53,990
There are none who can.

610
00:49:55,090 --> 00:49:58,089
Against the power of Mordor...

611
00:49:58,090 --> 00:50:02,090
...there can be no victory.

612
00:50:02,690 --> 00:50:07,089
We must join with him, Gandalf.

613
00:50:07,090 --> 00:50:10,790
We must join with Sauron.

614
00:50:12,090 --> 00:50:15,289
It would be wise, my friend.

615
00:50:15,290 --> 00:50:16,889
Tell me...

616
00:50:16,890 --> 00:50:18,889
...friend...

617
00:50:18,890 --> 00:50:24,790
...when did Saruman the Wise abandon reason for madness?

618
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:46,000
<i><font color="#FF0000">♫ Ash Burz-Durbagu burzum-ishi</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(One for the Dark Lord on his dark throne)</font></i>

619
00:50:46,500 --> 00:50:50,900
<i><font color="#FF0000">♫ Daghburz-ishi</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(In the land of Mordor)</font></i>

620
00:50:51,000 --> 00:50:59,900
<i><font color="#FF0000">♫ Makha gulshu darulu</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Where the shadows lie)</font></i>

621
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:20,000
<i><font color="#FF0000">♫ Ash Burz-Durbagu burzum-ishi</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(One for the Dark Lord on his dark throne)</font></i>

622
00:51:02,990 --> 00:51:05,789
I gave you the chance of...

623
00:51:05,790 --> 00:51:08,689
...aiding me willingly...

624
00:51:08,690 --> 00:51:14,190
...but you have elected the way of pain!

625
00:51:36,200 --> 00:51:38,299
Mr. Frodo?

626
00:51:38,300 --> 00:51:41,500
Frodo? Frodo!

627
00:51:41,500 --> 00:51:44,789
- I thought I'd lost you.
- What are you taking about?

628
00:51:44,790 --> 00:51:48,699
- It's just something Gandalf said.
- What did he say?

629
00:51:48,700 --> 00:51:52,899
"Don't you lose him, Samwise Gamgee."
And I don't mean to.

630
00:51:52,900 --> 00:51:57,900
Sam, we're still in the Shire.
What could possibly happen?

631
00:51:59,400 --> 00:52:00,699
Frodo.

632
00:52:00,700 --> 00:52:03,199
- Merry, it's Frodo Baggins.
- Hello, Frodo.

633
00:52:03,200 --> 00:52:05,089
Get off him.

634
00:52:05,090 --> 00:52:06,699
Come on, Frodo.

635
00:52:06,700 --> 00:52:08,989
What's the meaning of this?

636
00:52:08,990 --> 00:52:13,299
You've been into Farmer Maggot's crop!

637
00:52:13,300 --> 00:52:16,399
You get back here!

638
00:52:16,400 --> 00:52:17,999
Get out of my field!

639
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:20,999
You'll know the devil if I catch up with you!

640
00:52:21,000 --> 00:52:24,099
I don't know why he's so upset.
It's only a couple of carrots.

641
00:52:24,100 --> 00:52:25,399
And some cabbages.

642
00:52:25,400 --> 00:52:28,499
And those three bags of potatoes
that we lifted last week.

643
00:52:28,500 --> 00:52:32,799
- And then the mushrooms the week before.
- Yes, Pippin. My point is...

644
00:52:32,800 --> 00:52:35,199
...he's clearly overreacting.

645
00:52:35,200 --> 00:52:38,100
Run!

646
00:52:50,100 --> 00:52:53,799
Oh, that was close.

647
00:52:53,800 --> 00:52:57,899
I think I've broken something.

648
00:52:57,900 --> 00:53:00,399
Trust a Brandybuck and a Took!

649
00:53:00,400 --> 00:53:04,299
What? That was just a detour.
A short cut.

650
00:53:04,300 --> 00:53:08,000
- Short cut to what?
- Mushrooms!

651
00:53:15,300 --> 00:53:18,200
That's mine.

652
00:53:19,500 --> 00:53:21,699
That's nice, Merry.

653
00:53:21,700 --> 00:53:23,899
Here's a nice one, Sam.

654
00:53:23,900 --> 00:53:27,800
I think we should get off the road.

655
00:53:35,700 --> 00:53:37,199
Get off the road!

656
00:53:37,200 --> 00:53:40,100
Quick!

657
00:53:51,400 --> 00:53:54,300
Be quiet!

658
00:54:41,200 --> 00:54:45,500
<i><font color="#FF0000">Gulshu durbgu</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Lord of shadows)</font></i>

659
00:54:59,200 --> 00:55:02,800
What was that?

660
00:55:16,970 --> 00:55:26,459
<i><font color="#778899">♫ Nêpâm nêd</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(We grasp for ourselves)</font></i>

661
00:55:34,100 --> 00:55:36,299
Anything?

662
00:55:36,300 --> 00:55:38,499
Nothing.

663
00:55:38,500 --> 00:55:41,309
What is going on?

664
00:55:41,310 --> 00:55:46,410
That Black Rider was looking for something.
Or someone.

665
00:55:46,410 --> 00:55:48,609
Frodo?

666
00:55:48,610 --> 00:55:51,110
Get down!

667
00:56:06,510 --> 00:56:09,809
I have to leave the Shire.

668
00:56:09,810 --> 00:56:12,309
Sam and I must get to Bree.

669
00:56:12,310 --> 00:56:15,109
Right.

670
00:56:15,110 --> 00:56:18,810
Bucklebury Ferry. Follow me.

671
00:56:25,710 --> 00:56:28,209
Run!

672
00:56:28,210 --> 00:56:31,610
This way! Follow me!

673
00:56:33,910 --> 00:56:36,310
Run!

674
00:56:42,970 --> 00:56:51,459
<i><font color="#778899">♫ Nêbâbîtham Magânanê</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(We renounce our Maker)</font></i>

675
00:56:48,110 --> 00:56:51,310
Get the rope, Sam!

676
00:56:51,970 --> 00:56:56,459
<i><font color="#778899">♫ Bârî’n Katharâd</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Lords of Eternal Life)</font></i>

677
00:56:52,510 --> 00:56:54,809
Frodo!

678
00:56:54,810 --> 00:56:56,608
Run, Frodo!

679
00:56:56,609 --> 00:56:59,459
<i><font color="#778899">♫ Nidir nênâ</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(We are the Nine)</font></i>

680
00:56:56,610 --> 00:56:57,809
Go!
- Hurry!

681
00:56:57,810 --> 00:57:01,409
Frodo, come on!

682
00:56:59,970 --> 00:57:05,459
<i><font color="#778899">♫ Dâur-ad</font></i>
<i><font color="#FFFF00">(Darkness)</font></i>

683
00:57:01,410 --> 00:57:04,910
- Come on! Faster!
- Jump!

684
00:57:18,410 --> 00:57:23,910
- How far to the nearest crossing?
- The Brandywine Bridge. 20 miles.

685
00:57:37,210 --> 00:57:40,210
Come on.

686
00:57:49,910 --> 00:57:54,710
- What do you want?
- We're heading for the Prancing Pony.

687
00:57:56,810 --> 00:57:59,809
Hobbits. Four hobbits!

688
00:57:59,810 --> 00:58:04,309
What's more, out of the Shire by your talk.
What business brings you to Bree?

689
00:58:04,310 --> 00:58:08,509
We wish to stay at the inn.
Our business is our own.

690
00:58:08,510 --> 00:58:11,209
All right young sir, I meant no offense.

691
00:58:11,210 --> 00:58:14,009
It's my job to ask questions after nightfall.

692
00:58:14,010 --> 00:58:17,009
There's talk of strange folk abroad.

693
00:58:17,010 --> 00:58:20,610
Can't be too careful.

694
00:58:38,910 --> 00:58:43,710
Out of the way!
Watch where you're walking.

695
00:59:06,410 --> 00:59:09,009
Excuse me.

696
00:59:09,010 --> 00:59:12,009
Good evening, little masters.
What can I do for you?

697
00:59:12,010 --> 00:59:18,309
If you're looking for accommodation, we got
some nice cozy hobbit-sized rooms available.

698
00:59:18,310 --> 00:59:24,009
Always proud to cater to little folk, Mister...?

699
00:59:24,010 --> 00:59:27,409
Underhill. My name's Underhill.

700
00:59:27,410 --> 00:59:30,109
- Underhill, yeah.
- We're friends of Gandalf the Grey.

701
00:59:30,110 --> 00:59:33,609
- Can you tell him we've arrived?
- Gandalf?

702
00:59:33,610 --> 00:59:36,209
Gandalf.

703
00:59:36,210 --> 00:59:38,109
Oh, yes...

704
00:59:38,110 --> 00:59:40,509
...I remember. Elderly chap.

705
00:59:40,510 --> 00:59:43,819
Big grey beard, pointy hat.

706
00:59:43,820 --> 00:59:47,120
Not seen him for six months.

707
00:59:52,520 --> 00:59:55,320
What do we do now?

708
01:00:00,940 --> 01:00:02,339
Sam...

709
01:00:02,340 --> 01:00:05,640
...he'll be here. He'll come.

710
01:00:07,030 --> 01:00:10,530
Get out of my way!

711
01:00:11,530 --> 01:00:13,329
What's that?

712
01:00:13,330 --> 01:00:16,139
This, my friend, is a pint.

713
01:00:16,140 --> 01:00:18,039
It comes in pints?

714
01:00:18,040 --> 01:00:23,040
- I'm getting one.
- You got a whole half already!

715
01:00:28,030 --> 01:00:33,230
That fellow's done nothing but
stare at you since we arrived.

716
01:00:35,530 --> 01:00:38,430
Excuse me.

717
01:00:38,830 --> 01:00:43,029
That man in the corner. Who is he?

718
01:00:43,030 --> 01:00:47,529
He's one of them Rangers. They're dangerous
folk they are, wandering the wilds.

719
01:00:47,530 --> 01:00:53,430
What his right name is, I've never heard,
but 'round here he's known as Strider.

720
01:00:54,430 --> 01:00:57,130
Strider.

721
01:01:08,730 --> 01:01:13,330
Baggins...

722
01:01:15,030 --> 01:01:19,430
Baggins...

723
01:01:22,330 --> 01:01:25,929
Baggins...

724
01:01:25,930 --> 01:01:29,029
Baggins...

725
01:01:29,030 --> 01:01:32,629
<i>Baggins...
Baggins? Sure, I know a Baggins.</i>

726
01:01:32,630 --> 01:01:35,429
He's over there. Frodo Baggins.

727
01:01:35,430 --> 01:01:38,629
He's my second cousin,
once removed on his mother's side...

728
01:01:38,630 --> 01:01:42,330
...and my third cousin, twice removed....

729
01:01:45,430 --> 01:01:48,630
- Pippin!
- Steady on, Frodo.

730
01:02:16,730 --> 01:02:20,630
You cannot hide.

731
